d, Argyll, Schotland","Toward Cowal, Argyll, Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1334–1385":"1334–1385","1330–1385":"1330–1385","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1374–Female":"1374–Deceased","1381–1433":"1381–1433","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","about 1381":"about 1381","1334":"1334","1433":"1433","Abt 1374":"about 1374","1385":"1385","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","before 1370":"before 1370","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kerry, Toward Cowal, Argyll, Scotland":"Toward, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Toward, Argyll, Scotland":"Toward, Argyll, Scotland","Toward Cowal, Argyll, Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Munn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (southwestern): variant of   McMunn  .","English: from Middle English <i>Munne</i>, representing an Old Norse male personal name, <i>Munni</i> or <i>Munnr</i>, originally a nickname from Old Norse <i>munnr</i> ‘mouth’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>mun</i> ‘mouth’ (Old Norse <i>munnr</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"McMunn","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Munna</b> (<i>McIlMunn</i>) ‘son of the servant (or devotee) of (Saint) <i>Munnu</i>’, <i>Munnu</i> being a pet name for Saint Fintan of Taghmon. This name, which is also found in the form <i>Mundu</i>, from earlier <i>Mo-Fhindu</i>, is a hypocoristic form of <i>Fionntan</i> with the affective prefix <i>mo-</i> ‘my’. Although Fintan was an Irish saint, this surname appears to have been coined in Scotland, where there was a place called Kilmun ‘Saint Munnu's church’, near Inverary."]},{"name":"Mun","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Yong, Chong, Hyung, In, Song, Bok, Dae, Hui, Jae, Kwang, Kyong, Kyong Tae, Kyung, Myung, Ae, Cheol, Chul, Chul Ho, Chung, Hak, Hong Suk, Hyung Chul, In Ho.","English: variant of   Munn  .","Korean: there are two Chinese characters for the surname <i>Mun</i>. Although some records indicate that there are as many as 131 Mun clans, only three can be traced. The founding ancestor of the oldest of these, the Namp’yŏng Mun clan, was named Mun Ta-sŏng and was born in 472. According to legend, he was found by Shilla King Chabi Maripkan in a stone box at the end of a rainbow by a lotus pond. The Chinese character Mun was inscribed in the box, so the king gave that as a surname to the child. The founders of the other two Mun clans were originally named   Cha   and   Kim  , but after studying in China they changed their names to Mun (the Chinese character <i>Mun</i> means ‘writing’ or ‘literature’)."]},{"name":"Munns","meanings":["English: variant of   Munn   or   Mund  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Christina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Christina Munn was born in 1334, in Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland. She married Duncan Lamont 4th Chief of Clan Lamont before 1370, in Toward, Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1385, in Scotland, at the age of 51, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1334–1385":"1334–1385","1330–1385":"1330–1385","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1381–1433":"1381–1433","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1381":"umbes 1381","1334":"1334","1433":"1433","Abt 1374":"umbes 1374","1385":"1385","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","before 1370":"enne 1370","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kerry, Toward Cowal